## **What Is an Oval Cut Diamond? The Complete Definition**

**An oval cut diamond is an elliptical modified brilliant-cut diamond with 57–58 facets — essentially a round brilliant stretched into an elongated ellipse.**

The oval cut is classified by GIA as a "modified brilliant" — it uses the same triangular and kite-shaped facet arrangement as a round brilliant but adapted to the elliptical outline. This means the oval retains the round brilliant's fundamental optical mechanism (light enters through the table, reflects through the pavilion, returns through the table) while adding the size and silhouette advantages of an elongated outline.

I'm **Farzana Hasan**, a GIA Expert. The oval cut has experienced the most dramatic popularity surge of any diamond shape in recent years — driven by celebrity engagement rings, social media visibility, and buyers recognizing the combination of brilliant sparkle, apparent size advantage, and meaningful price savings over round.

This guide covers everything: the bow-tie physics, the ideal proportions GIA doesn't grade, the complete live price data from Blue Nile, and the lab-grown arbitrage that makes oval the dominant value shape in 2026. Full credentials at **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**.

