8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$9,510</a></strong></td><td><strong>2/10 — Extreme Outlier Warning.</strong> A massive database anomaly. This stone commands a staggering $2,270 premium over an identical D-IF stone on the same list. This massive price inflation likely stems from an old consignment layout or a highly specific, non-standard proportions matrix. Avoid entirely.</td></tr></tbody></table>

**Critical data insight — the most revealing comparison in the 1ct data:**

A D-VVS2 at $5,730 and an E-VS1 at $5,720 are priced within $10 of each other. For most buyers, the E-VS1 is the superior purchase — E color is only one grade below D (indistinguishable in a ring setting) and VS1 is the clarity sweet spot for ovals. The D-VVS2 spends money on a D-color premium that delivers no visible difference and a VVS2 premium that delivers no visible difference. This $10 price difference hides fundamentally different value propositions.

**The $9,510 D-IF outlier:** This stone is priced $2,270 above the other D-IF at $7,240 for identical GIA grade specifications. This extreme premium reflects superior L/W ratio, proportion quality, and likely near-ideal depth and table percentages. This is the clearest illustration in the entire 1ct dataset of how proportions drive price within the same grade.

