### **Oval vs. Round Brilliant**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Oval</th><th>Round Brilliant</th><th>Winner</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Brilliance</strong></td><td>Near-round — excellent</td><td>Maximum</td><td><strong>Round</strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — The Optical Benchmark.</strong> The round brilliant is mathematically engineered for perfect internal light reflection. Every facet angle is optimized to return maximum fire to the eye. While a masterfully cut oval delivers gorgeous, explosive scintillation, its elongated geometry can never match the flawless, symmetrical light return of a round stone.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Price <small>(1ct G-VS1)</small></strong></td><td>~$4,400–$5,000</td><td>~$4,000–$4,400</td><td><strong>Oval</strong> <small>— slightly less</small></td><td><strong>10/10 — Capital Efficiency King.</strong> Because ovals align beautifully with the natural shape of rough diamond crystals, diamond cutters lose far less raw material during manufacturing. This structural advantage translates directly into a permanent 15% to 25% cash discount over an equivalent round stone, keeping your capital highly liquid.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Apparent face-up size</strong></td><td>10–15% larger</td><td>Standard</td><td><strong>Oval</strong></td><td><strong>10/10 — The Spread Arbitrage.</strong> Carat is simply a measure of weight, not visual surface area. Round stones carry significant mass deep in their bellies, whereas ovals distribute their weight across an elongated face-up profile. A 1-carat oval visually mimics a 1.15-carat round, maximizing your visual return per dollar.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Bow-tie risk</strong></td><td>Yes — evaluate on video</td><td>None</td><td><strong>Round</strong></td><td><strong>6/10 — The Inherent Geometry Tax.</strong> The elongated facet design of an oval makes a central dark shadow—the bow-tie effect—a physical inevitability. Round diamonds carry zero bow-tie risk due to their perfect radial symmetry. Buying an oval demands a strict 4K video or hands-on audit to ensure this shadow behaves naturally.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>GIA cut grade</strong></td><td>Not issued</td><td>Yes</td><td><strong>Round</strong></td><td><strong>7/10 — Certification Blindspots.</strong> GIA explicitly leaves the cut grade column blank for fancy shapes, forcing buyers to independently analyze complex table (53–63%) and depth (58–64%) ratios. Round brilliants benefit from strict, standardized GIA "Excellent" ratings, providing instant quality assurance on paper.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Finger-lengthening</strong></td><td>Significant</td><td>None</td><td><strong>Oval</strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — Aesthetic Finger Coverage.</strong> The north-to-south orientation of an oval creates a beautiful slimming illusion on the hand. Round brilliants sit as a fixed, self-contained focal anchor, whereas the sweeping lines of an oval elegantly draw the eye upward, complementing the hand’s natural proportions.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Market share 2026</strong></td><td>~25% (growing)</td><td>~50% (stable)</td><td><strong>Round</strong> <small>(established)</small></td><td><strong>8/10 — The Cultural Shift.</strong> In mid-2026, the round brilliant remains the undisputed bedrock of the fine jewelry industry, holding half the global market. However, the oval’s rapid climb to a 25% share reflects a massive cultural shift toward minimalist, modern luxury. It is the fastest-growing fancy cut in contemporary design portfolios.</td></tr></tbody></table>

