### **Oval vs. Cushion Cut**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Oval</th><th>Cushion</th><th>Winner</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Brilliance style</strong></td><td>Elongated brilliant</td><td>Brilliant <small>(chunky or crushed ice)</small></td><td><strong>Personal preference</strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — The Scintillation Divide.</strong> Ovals disperse light in elongated, rapid needle-like bursts across their length. Cushions offer an architectural choice: "Chunky" cuts emit broad, slow-flashing beams (similar to old mine cuts), while "Crushed Ice" configurations generate dense, tight pinpricks of light. Neither out-performs the other; it is an aesthetic preference.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Price <small>(1ct H-VS2)</small></strong></td><td>~$4,800–$5,200</td><td>~$1,760–$1,800</td><td><strong>Cushion</strong> <small>— significant value</small></td><td><strong>10/10 — The Budget Arbitrage Champion.</strong> This price chasm stems from extreme consumer demand trends in mid-2026. Ovals carry a steep premium because they are the fastest-growing fashion silhouette on the market. Cushions bypass this trend tax completely, offering identical carat mass for a fraction of the capital investment.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Apparent size</strong></td><td>Larger <small>(elongated)</small></td><td>Compact</td><td><strong>Oval</strong></td><td><strong>10/10 — Visual Footprint Dominance.</strong> Carat is strictly weight, not surface dimension. Cushions are deep-bellied shapes that concentrate their mass underneath the stone. Ovals spread their weight horizontally and vertically. A 1-carat oval consistently delivers a striking ~8.5 x 6.0mm face-up footprint, easily eclipsing the square outline of a cushion.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Color retention</strong></td><td>Moderate</td><td>High — cushion traps color</td><td><strong>Oval</strong> <small>— more forgiving</small></td><td><strong>8/10 — The Body Tint Tax.</strong> The internal pavilion architecture of a cushion cut works like a light-trapping chamber, which naturally concentrates body color. If you drop below a G color in a cushion, warm yellow undertones become immediately visible. Ovals are significantly more forgiving, masking minor tints within their brilliant end-facets.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Bow-tie risk</strong></td><td>Yes</td><td>Rare</td><td><strong>Cushion</strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — Optical Security.</strong> Cushions utilize a symmetrical, concentrated facet pattern that keeps light return uniform across the center table, making bow-ties incredibly rare. Ovals are permanently exposed to this visual hazard. Buying an oval requires a rigorous 4K video audit, while a cushion provides instant optical security.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Finger lengthening</strong></td><td>Significant</td><td>None</td><td><strong>Oval</strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — Anatomic Elegance.</strong> The vertical orientation of an oval creates a beautiful optical illusion that slenders and elongates the wearer's hand. Cushions act as a self-contained, square focal anchor. While cushions look exceptionally beautiful in classic halo settings, they offer none of the hand-slimming geometry native to the oval footprint.</td></tr></tbody></table>

